{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488794"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:57:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:57:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"542"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/542"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.25,0.07,0.1,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81891"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/542"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67168"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"452"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3381"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81891"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of painless swellings in the right side of his scrotum. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are several firm, flesh-coloured nodules visible in the scrotal skin (Image). The nodules are mobile over deeper tissues and non-tender. The testes are normal to palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hidradenitis suppurativa","Teratoma of the testis","Varicocele","Encysted hydrocele","Epidermoid cyst"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple asymptomatic nodules in the superficial layers of the scrotal skin. \u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are the most likely diagnosis, as they characteristically present as firm, flesh-coloured or yellowish round nodules that are fixed to the skin surface but mobile over deeper tissues. They result from proliferation of epidermal cells within the dermis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHidradenitis suppurativa\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with painful, inflamed nodules and abscesses involving the apocrine sweat glands. It often has a chronic, recurrent course with sinus tract formation and scarring, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricocele\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a soft, compressible mass described as feeling like a \u0027bag of worms\u0027 due to dilated veins of the pampiniform plexus. It would be palpable along the spermatic cord rather than in the superficial skin layers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncysted hydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a fluid-filled swelling along the spermatic cord. It would be deeper than the skin surface and typically presents as a single, translucent swelling rather than multiple nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETeratoma of the testis\u003C/strong\u003E would present as a firm mass arising from the testis itself, not the scrotal skin. It would be palpable as an intratesticular mass on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEpidermoid cysts are benign lesions that typically do not require treatment unless they become infected or cause cosmetic concerns. Simple excision can be performed if treatment is desired.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Epidermoid cysts present as firm, flesh-coloured or yellowish round nodules fixed to the skin surface but mobile over deeper layers.","Location in the superficial skin layers helps distinguish epidermoid cysts from deeper scrotal pathologies like varicoceles or testicular masses.","Multiple asymptomatic scrotal epidermoid cysts do not require treatment unless they become infected or cause cosmetic concerns."],"references":["Epidermoid cyst [Internet]. Epidermoid cyst | DermNet NZ. [cited 2021Jul27]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/epidermoid-cyst/","Hidradenitis suppurativa [Internet]. Hidradenitis suppurativa | DermNet NZ. [cited 2021Jul27]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/hidradenitis-suppurativa/","Pomajzl AJ. Appendix testes Torsion [Internet]. StatPearls [Internet]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2021 [cited 2021Jul27]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546994/","Wani I, Rather M, Naikoo G, Gul I, Bhat Z, Baba A. Encysted hydrocele of cord in an adult misdiagnosed as irreducible hernia: a case report. Oman Med J. 2009;24(3):218-219. doi:10.5001/omj.2009.43"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67168"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"542"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18363"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18363"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/865343e4-4368-4c58-8bfb-eee0178c2a8f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/865343e4-4368-4c58-8bfb-eee0178c2a8f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67168"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T11:50:17+1